<%- include('partials/header') %>

    <div class="page-container">
        <div class="page-header">
            <h1>🔐 Change Password</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">Vulnerability: CSRF — Cross-Site Request Forgery (A01:2021)</p>
        </div>

        <% if (error) { %>
            <div class="alert alert-error">⚠️ <%= error %>
            </div>
            <% } %>
                <% if (success) { %>
                    <div class="alert alert-success">✅ <%= success %>
                    </div>
                    <% } %>

                        <div class="card">
                            <p class="text-muted mb-2">Logged in as: <strong>
                                    <%= user ? user.username : 'Unknown' %>
                                </strong></p>
                            <form method="POST" action="/change-password" id="change-password-form">
                                <!-- 🔴 Notice: No CSRF token in this form! -->
                                <div class="form-group">
                                    <label for="new_password">New Password</label>
                                    <input type="password" id="new_password" name="new_password" class="form-control"
                                        placeholder="Enter new password" required>
                                </div>
                                <button type="submit" class="btn btn-danger btn-block">Change Password</button>
                            </form>
                        </div>

                        <div class="hint-box">
                            <button class="hint-toggle">💡 Show Attack Hints</button>
                            <div class="hint-content">
                                <h4>🧠 How CSRF Works (Simple Explanation)</h4>
                                <p>
                                    Look at this form — it just sends the new password to the server. It doesn't include
                                    any
                                    <strong>secret token</strong> to prove the request came from this page.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    An attacker can create a <strong>fake HTML page</strong> that automatically submits
                                    a hidden
                                    form to <code>/change-password</code>. If a logged-in user visits the attacker's
                                    page, their
                                    browser will send the request with their cookies — changing their password!
                                </p>

                                <h4 class="mt-2">🎯 Try This Attack</h4>
                                <p>Create an HTML file on your computer with this code, then open it in the same
                                    browser:</p>
                                <p><code>
        &lt;form method="POST" action="http://localhost:3000/change-password"&gt;<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;input type="hidden" name="new_password" value="hacked123"&gt;<br>
        &lt;/form&gt;<br>
        &lt;script&gt;document.forms[0].submit()&lt;/script&gt;
      </code></p>
                                <p>When opened, it <strong>silently changes the logged-in user's password</strong> to
                                    "hacked123"!</p>

                                <h4 class="mt-2">🛡️ How to Fix It</h4>
                                <p>Add a <strong>CSRF token</strong> — a unique, random value in the form that the
                                    server validates.
                                    Also require the <strong>current password</strong> before allowing changes.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
    </div>

    <%- include('partials/footer') %>